stling Moneyback Taffeta Silk,\nguaranteed extra full' width, plaited\nand tucked, worth $8.50, at $7.50.\nStylish Petticoats of Plain Black\nmercerized Sateen, extra good qual\nity and very wide,, all lengths, reg\nular price $1.25, Special at 98c.\nGEO. D. WHEATLEY.\nAmericus, Ga.\nAutumn Sale of Kid Gloves.\nOur Fall Importation of Kid Gloves\nare in evidence, a finer showing of\nstandard, reputable Kid Gloves has\nnever been made in this section.\nPrices SI.OO, $1.25, $2.25, $3.50, $4.00.\nUnder we arfor Men, Women\nThere are 2 points about our\nUnderwear equipment that we strong\nly emphasize; quality and generosity\nof size. We never show Jobby under\nwear for it always pays to get the\nbest at 25, 50, 75, SI.OO.\n\u201cRubens\u201d Infants shirt in cotton\nor wool. Also silk and wool at\n25, 50 and 75c each.\nMen\u2019s Negligee Shirts.\nJust received ah ut 150 doz. Men\u2019s\nfine Negligee Shirts in light grounds\nwith figures, plaids and stripes, regu\nlar price 75c, Special for this week\nat 50c.\nCarpets.\nThe best product of the best mak\ners for you to select from. Ingrains\nTapestry Brussells, Body Brussells\nand Velvets, all are in readiness at\n75, 85\u201e SI.OO, $1.15, $1.25, $1.50. Made,\nI Laid and Lined.\nThe Rug Collection.\nFrom tire small mat to the largest\ncarpet size rug. They are ail here\nand in variety great enough to suit\nany taste.\nSyrmina Rugs from 98c to $6.50.\nAxmlnister Rugs 98c to $1.50.\nJute Rugs 80c to $4.00.\nAxminister Art Squares, all sizes,\n$12.50 to $30.00.\nTHE AMERICUS DAILY TIMES-RECORDER, FRIDAY OCTOBER 18, 1907.\nNOW 18 THE TIME TO ACT.\nj There is a time for everything. A\ntime to think, a time to defer and a\n/ilWl time to act.\nNow is the time to act\u2014to buy Real\nEstate. How are these bargains:\nA splendid little rental property\njEgratyraaijp paying $126.00 per annum for SBOO. In\n-5) come more than 15 per cent.\nA new 5-rom house, well located\nVacant lots in all parts of the city\n\u201cwhich are sure to enhance rapidly\nin value.\u201d Sold at rock bottom prices\nand on easy payment plan. Many a\nman has lived to regret missing a real estate bargain that has proved gold\nen. MORAL: Act NOW.\nLEE\nThe Real Estate and Insurance Man.\nSOCIAL AND reRSOML Lift\nBrevities That Tell of Movements of Amerieus\nfolks and friends.\nCombs, 35 and 50c engraved free.\nThos. L. Bell, the leading jeweler.\n8-2 t.\nFine harness carried in stock or\nmade to order at Bagley\u2019s; wholesale\nand retail.\nWANTED \u2014An iron safe at once.\nAddress P. 0. Box 184. 17-2 t.\nWillis Goldthwaite registered from\nBirmingham yesterday, among the ar\nrivals at the Windsor.\nMrs. Drewery, of Griffin, is the\nguest of her sister, Mrs. Sallie H.\nGyles, arriving yesterday.\nMiss Floyd Fort returned home\nyesterday from a visit of some length\npleasantly spent with relatives and\nfriends in Atlanta.\nMrs. C. S. Gurr of Vienna, is the\nguest of Mrs. H. B. Mashburn for\nseveral days at her residence on\nFurlow street.\nMiss Blanche Pryor, the charming\n'guest of her aunt, Mrs. R. L. May\nnard for several days, returned to\nSmithville yesterday.\nL\nEditor John Triplett, the genial bach\neloric helmsman of the Thomasville\nTimes-Enterprise, wag in Amerieus\nyesterday, en route Home from a trip\nout West.\ndelighted with the\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK\n\u201cYes, we have been more than\ngratified with the season\u2019s business'\nup to date,\u201d said Mr. D. R. Andrews,\nmanager for the Rylander Shoe Com\npany yesterday in discussing business\nconditions.\n\u201cOur attractive store is an excellent\nadvertisement for us and for Am\nericas. We are proud to think that\nwe began the movement for the re\nnovation and beautification of mer\ncantile establishments in Amerieus\nthis year, that lead to so many import\nant changes. The results have been\nall that we could wish for. Our\ngreatly increased stock, our ability\nto display it properly, and the satis\nfaction that customers generally de\nrive froin pleasant surroundings, have\nall had their effect. Then we adhere\nrigidly to the determination to please\nevery man, woman and child taht\nbuys from us, no matter how small\nthe purchase may be. We endeavor to\nsend every customer away thorough\nly satisfied that full value has been\nhad for the money expended. We\nare building for the future all the\ntime and laying foundations for a\ngreater business every year. We\nanticipate a continued increase in\nour business right along.\u201d\nALLEGED THAT WIFE\nTHREATENED TO KILL\nATLANTA, GA., October 17.\n(Special)\u2014John R. Cox today enter\ned suit for total divorce from his\nwife. The petition alleges that Mrs.\nCox threatened to kill the children\nand in many ways humiliated the pe\ntitioner. She is also charged with\nlying in bed of morning while the\nhusband built the' fires and prepared\nthe breakfast.\nNotice.\nWe understand some dealers are\nselling Amerieus Maid Cigars 6 for\n25 cents. We will refuse to sell any\ndealer the above cigar if he sells them\nat less than 5 cents straight. Custo\nmers will do us a favor by reporting\nany violation to this rule.\nVery respectfully,\nAMERICUS CIGAR CO.\n17-lwk.\ni Call up Loving\u2019s Stables, phone 81,\nfor baggage transfer. ts.\nBack cobs furnished and hand\nsomely engraved for 50c and 75c at\nDaniels\u2019 the reliable jeweler.\nMr. and Mrs. B. T. Peacock of\nBeuna Vista, were visitors in Amerieus\nyesterday.\nJames Evans of Gainesville was a\nbusiness visitor in Amerieus yester\nday morning.\nL. T. Boyd, of Tennille, was in Am\nericus yesterday morning, coming\nhere upon business.\nW. M. Breedlove of Athens was\namong the many visitors coming to\nAmerieus yesterday.\nJ. IV. Bogle of Dalton, Ga\u201e was\nin the city yesterday and stopped\nat the Hotel Windsor.\nCol. W. A. Dodson went up to At\nlanta this morning upon legal busi\nness of importance.\nSee Bagley's buggies before you buy\nSpecial price to cash customers or\nwill sell on terms to suit customer.\nj Miss Jennie Hollis and sister, Mrs.\n'Grantland Rice, who have been spend\ning some time in New York City, are\nexpected to return home shortly./\n\nWEDDING AT HOME IS\nA QUIET AFFAIRS\nMiss Laurie Speer and Mr. John\nH. Rushin were united in marriage\nat 4 o\u2019clock yesjerday afternoon at\nthe residence of the bride\u2019s mother,\nMrs. Jennie Speer, on Forsyth street.\nOn account of the recent illness of\nMiss Speer the marriage was a very\nquiet one and solemnized by Rev.\nO. P. Gilbert, of First Baptist church,\nin the presence of the family, and\nnear relatives only. The bride is a\nvery charming young woman and has\nmany friends here to whom the an\nnouncement of her marriage will be\nof much interest. Mr. Rushin comes\nfrom Montezuma, and for a year or\ntwo has been a valuable attache of\nthe Amerieus Printing Co.\nCLEBURNE COUNTY TO\nVOTE ON PROHIBITION\nBIRMINGHAM, ALA., Oct 17.\n(Special)\u2014Eigh t hundred names,\nover half of the voting strength of\nCleburne county, have been signed\nto a petition calling for prohibition\nelection. An active campaign will\nbe started at once, or rather it Is\nalready in progress: It is regarded\nas assured that prohibition will win.\nEvery county in the state which has\nthus far voted has banished the sa\nloons.\nNEGRO DUE TO HANG\nTODAY GOES TO PEN\nATLANTA, GA., October 17.\n(Special)\u2014Gov. Smith commuted to\nlife imprisonment today the death\nsentence of Henry Brown, colored,\nwho was to have been hanged to\nmorrow in Crisp county for the mur\nder o fanother negro. The lighter\npenalty was imposed on allegations\nof newly discovered evidence.\nSENTENCE COMMUTED\nPRISONER RELEASED\nATLANTA, GA., October 17.\n(Special)\u2014Gov. Smith commuted the\nterm of L. D. Strong, of Macon,\nsent up for three years for killing\nHenry Smith, a printer, for Insult\ning his sister. The time cut off from\nhis sentence enables him to leave\nprison at once.\nAnsleys Store News\nQueen Summer has abdicated\nher throne and Prince Autumn\nreigns supreme. This store is his\nloyal subject and the great stock of\nautumn merchandise is here in re\ncognition of his advent.\nANOTHER GREAT and\nBusy Week in\nLadies Ready-to-Wear\ns\nDepartment.\nThe magnificent stock we are\nshowing, the extraordinarily low\nprices we are making together with\nthe comfortable and convenient ar\nrangement of the department locat\ned on the first floor is making an\nenormous increase in the business.\nYou will find upon examination\nand comparison that our suits are\nfrom $2.50 to SIO.OO cheaper than\nwhat others ask, our skirts from\nsi.oo to $5.00 cheaper.\nSee the Mamilicent Tail\u00bbr-Made Suits SIO.OO to $75.00\nSec the Beautifully Tailored Skirts, $5,7.50,10 and Up-\nSee the Swell Broadcloth aad Oiiisr Coats S5-B0 to $35.\nSee the Elegant Rubberized ST Raincoats $lO to $25,\nSee the Most Beautiful Voille Skirts Ever Shown Here.\nSee the Finest All-Wool Panama Skirts in America for $5.\nSee the Best Line Misses Wool Skitis Ever Shown Here-\nSee the Grandest Line Silk laifeta Petticoats for ssin U-S.\nSee the Largesi Line Taffeta Petticoats in blacks\nand Colons\nSee the Best Line Infants Coats, All Styles, Col\nors and Prices.\nSee the Lowest Prices (or First-Class Merchan\ndise You Have Ever Seen.\nSee the Finest and Best Line Silks and Woolen\nCress Goods in South Georgia.\nSea Eveiything in the Dry Goods Line Better\nThan Ever.\nChas. L. Ansley\nSuccessor to WHEATLEY ANSLEY.\nAgents: ButterickS Patterns and American Lad; Corsets","height":"29168","width":"19734"}}
